he concept of abstraction. Abstraction refers to the creation of new material substances and cultural values by detaching parts from existing substances and values. The abstractive process differs from the activity of extractive industries by its focus on the conceptual resources that conceal processes of exploitation associated with extraction. The study of abstraction can thus help us attune to the formal operations that make appropriations of value possible while disclosing the politics of extraction and of its representation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aMineral industrieszArctic regions. 0aNatural resourceszArctic regions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Natural Resource Extraction.2bisacsh  aAnthropology (General), Environmental Studies (General), Development Studies.1 aBennett, Mia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinovelli-Lang, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDokis, Carly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHepsø, Vidar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, Cymene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMason, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMason, Arthur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNuttall, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParmiggiani, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTimofeeva, Oxana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatts, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package: